Gold | [[2002 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2002 Moscow]] | 4\u00d7100 m freestyle }}\n{{MedalGold | 2002 Moscow | 4\u00d7100 m medley }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2004 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2004 Indianapolis]] | 100 m freestyle }}\n{{MedalGold | 2004 Indianapolis | 4\u00d7100 m freestyle }}\n{{MedalGold | 2004 Indianapolis | 4\u00d7100 m medley }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2006 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2006 Shanghai]] | 4\u00d7100 m medley }}\n{{MedalBronze | 2006 Shanghai | 4\u00d7100 m freestyle }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Pan Pacific Swimming Championships|Pan Pacific Championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2002 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships|2002 Yokohama]] | [[2002 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships \u2013 Men's 50 metre freestyle|50 m freestyle]] }}\n{{MedalGold | 2002 Yokohama | [[2002 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m medley]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2006 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships|2006 Victoria]] | [[2006 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100 m freestyle]] }}\n{{MedalGold | 2006 Victoria | [[2006 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m medley]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2010 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships|2010 Irvine]] | [[2010 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100 m freestyle]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[1999 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships|1999 Sydney]] | [[1999 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100 m freestyle]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | 2006 Victoria | [[2006 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre freestyle|100 m freestyle]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | 2002 Yokohama | [[2002 Pan Pacific Swimming Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100 m freestyle]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Swimming at the Summer Universiade|Universiade]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 1997 Summer Universiade|1997 Catania]] | 4\u00d7100 m freestyle }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Maccabiah Games]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2009 Maccabiah Games|2009 Israel]] | 50 m freestyle }}\n{{MedalGold | 2009 Israel | 100 m freestyle }}\n{{MedalGold | 2009 Israel | 4\u00d7100 m freestyle }}\n{{MedalGold | 2009 Israel | 4\u00d7100 m medley }}\n}}\n\n'''Jason Edward Lezak''' (born November 12, 1975) is an American swimming executive. He serves as the general manager of the Cali Condors a part of the [[International Swimming League]]. He is a former American competition swimmer representing team USA in four [[Olympic games]] winning a total of eight medals including four gold.\n\nJason grew up in [[Irvine, California]] as a well-rounded athlete. He began swimming at the age of five, played on the high school basketball team, and became a high school All-American in water polo. Early in his career it was noticeable that Jason excelled and enjoyed being a part of relays. Currently his performance on the [[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100-meter freestyle relay]] at the the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] is still the fastest relay split in history. Jason credits his background in team sports as a big part in his relay success. \n\nAs a proud husband and father, highly respected athlete and executive, Jason has become an inspiration to a wide variety of audiences. He successfully balances his family and business life with motivating others and sharing his stories.\n\n==Executive career==\nLezak serves as the general manager for the Cali Condors a part of the [[International Swimming League]]. In the first year of the league in 2019 the Condors finished 3rd place in the finals. In the off season he has continued to improve his team with some great additions looking to win the championship in 2020.\n\n==Swimming career==\n\n===Olympics===\nLezak has competed in four Olympic Games, in [[2000 Summer Olympics|2000]], [[2004 Summer Olympics|2004]], [[2008 Summer Olympics|2008]], and [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012]], and has won eight Olympic medals; two bronze, two silver, and four gold.  \n\n====2000 Olympics====\nLezak earned his first long-course international swimming gold medal at the [[2000 Summer Olympics]] in Sydney, where he was part of the [[Swimming at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100-meter medley relay]] in the Olympics in Sydney. He also won a silver medal in the [[Swimming at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100-meter freestyle relay]].\n\n====2004 Olympics====\nLezak competed in several events at the [[2004 Olympic Games]] in Athens, Greece, and was a member of the [[Swimming at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100-meter medley relay]] team that set a new world record and earned another gold medal at the games. Lezak also won a bronze medal in the [[Swimming at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100-meter freestyle relay]] and finished fifth in the [[Swimming at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 50 metre freestyle|50-meter freestyle]].\n\n====2008 Olympics====\nAt the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in Beijing, Lezak was the oldest male and team captain of the U.S. swim team.  He anchored the U.S. [[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100-meter freestyle relay]] team that won the gold medal and set a new world record. In the final 25 meters, Lezak overtook French team anchor [[Alain Bernard]] (the world record holder in the 100-meter freestyle going into the relay) to win gold despite Bernard having nearly a full body length's advantage when Lezak started his leg and half a body length 25 meters from the end. Lezak split a 46.06, the fastest 100-meter freestyle split in history by nearly six-tenths of a second (It is the fastest by 0.08 seconds now, Duncan Scott swam a 46.14s split in the 2019 World Championships 4x100 medley relay). The final time of the American team was 3:08:24, which was 3.99 seconds faster than the previous world record; the French team finished second at 3:08.32, eight one-hundredths (0.08) of a second behind\u2014the closest finish in the event's history. This was a crucial race for [[Michael Phelps]], because he needed it to complete the goal of winning eight gold medals in a single Olympic Games, breaking [[Mark Spitz]]'s record of seven gold medals at the [[1972 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"yahoo_reuters\">{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20080807/sp_nm/olympics_swimming_bernard_dc |title=I'm favorite and we'll smash U.S.: Bernard |accessdate=August 11, 2008 |publisher=Reuters |date=August 7, 2008 |author=Francois Thomazeau |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080817202914/http://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20080807/sp_nm/olympics_swimming_bernard_dc |archivedate=August 17, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nLezak also earned his first individual Olympic medal, having tied for bronze with [[Brazil]]ian swimmer [[C\u00e9sar Cielo Filho]] in the [[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 100 metre freestyle|100-meter freestyle]] with a time of 47.67.\n\nIn the final race of these games Lezak anchored the U.S. [[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m medley relay]] to a gold medal securing [[Michael Phelps]] final gold medal to break [[Mark Spitz]] record.\n\n====2012 Olympics====\nLezak qualified for his fourth Olympics at the [[2012 United States Olympic Trials (swimming)|2012 United States Olympic Trials]] in Omaha, Nebraska. His sixth-place finish in the Olympic Trial finals was good enough to reach the London Games as a member of the U.S. [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100-meter freestyle relay]] team.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2012/olympics/swimming/wires/06/29/2090.ap.oly.swm.us.swim.trials.jones/index.html | title = Lezak returns to Olympics | work = SI.com | publisher = [[Turner Broadcasting System]], Inc. | accessdate = June 30, 2012 | date=June 29, 2012}}</ref> At the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in London, United Kingdom, [[Jimmy Feigen]], [[Matt Grevers]], [[Ricky Berens]] and Lezak swam for the U.S. team in the preliminaries.  [[Nathan Adrian]], [[Michael Phelps]], [[Cullen Jones]] and [[Ryan Lochte]] swam in the finals, and together all these competitors earned a silver medal for the team's second-place finish in the finals.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/29/ryan-lochte-relay-france-4x100-phelps_n_1716913.html | title = Ryan Lochte Overtaken Late As France Wins Gold in 4x100-Meter Relay | work = HuffingtonPost | publisher = TheHuffingtonPost.com, Inc. | accessdate = July 31, 2012 | first=Chris | last=Greenberg | date=July 29, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Citation | url = https://www.jewishjournal.com/olympics/article/jason_lezak_likely_closes_olympics_career_with_a_silver_medal_20120731/ | title = Jason Lezak likely closes Olympics career with a silver medal | work = JewishJournal.com | publisher = Tribe Media Corp.  | accessdate = July 31, 2012}}</ref> Lezak became the first male swimmer in Olympic history to win [[List of multiple Olympic medalists in one event#Team events|four medals in the same event]], the 4\u00d7100-meter freestyle relay.\n\n===Short course competitions===\nIn short-course competitions, Lezak won five world championships: four relays including the 2002 4x100m freestyle and medley, and 2004 4x100m freestyle, and a gold in the 100-meter freestyle in 2004. Lezak has also won seven U.S. Championships, three times in the 50-meter freestyle and four in the 100-meter freestyle.\n\n===2009; Maccabiah Games===\n[[File:Jason Lezak 1.JPG|right|thumb|220px|Lezak at the [[2009 Maccabiah Games]].]]\nLezak passed up on attending the [[2009 World Aquatics Championships]] to compete in the 18th [[Maccabiah Games]] in Israel from July 12 to 29, 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://usaswimming.org/USASWeb/ViewNewsArticle.aspx?TabId=0&Alias=Rainbow&Lang=en&ItemId=2440&mid=2943 |title=Lezak partners with Maccabi USA/Sports for Israel }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Lezak was given the honor of lighting the Maccabiah torch at the Opening Ceremony.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jta.org/news/article/2009/07/13/1006476/maccabiah-opening-ceremony-set |title=Lezak lights torch at Maccabiah opening |date=July 13, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090716220149/http://jta.org/news/article/2009/07/13/1006476/maccabiah-opening-ceremony-set |archivedate=July 16, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref> At the [[2009 Maccabiah Games]], Lezak won gold medals in the 50-meter freestyle, 100-meter freestyle, 4\u00d7100-meter freestyle relay, and 4\u00d7100-meter medley relay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://presidiosports.com/2009/07/javanifard-lezak-make-splash-at-maccabiah-games/|title=Javanifard, Lezak make splash at Maccabiah Games|date=July 24, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2017 Maccabiah Games]], in the special 4x50m relay race between Israeli and American all-star teams, American Olympic champions Lezak, [[Lenny Krayzelburg]] (four Olympic golds), and [[Anthony Ervin]] (three Olympic golds), with masters swimmer Alex Blavatnik, swam a time of 1:48.23 and defeated Israeli Olympians [[Guy Barnea]], [[Yoav Bruck]], [[Eran Groumi]], and [[Tal Stricker]], who had a time of 1:51.25.<ref>[http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Sports/Records-fall-as-Olympians-shine-at-Maccabiah-Games-499449 \"Records fall as Olympians shine at Maccabiah Games,\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''The Jerusalem Post''.</ref>\n\n==Personal bests==\nHis personal bests (long-course) are:\n\n* 50 m freestyle: 21.90\n* 100 m freestyle: 47.58 (former American record)\n* 100 m freestyle relay split 46.06 (fastest relay split ever, even though [[FINA]] does not recognize world records for relay splits, unless they were in the opening leg, as only the opening leg is done from a stationary start, whereas later swimmers can lean over in the process of diving as the preceding swimmer is coming in)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Olympics}}\n* [[List of Jews in sports#Swimming|List of select Jewish swimmers]]\n* [[List of multiple Olympic gold medalists in one event]]\n* [[List of Olympic medalists in swimming (men)]]\n* [[List of United States records in swimming]]\n* [[List of World Aquatics Championships medalists in swimming (men)]]\n* [[List of world records in swimming]]\n* [[World record progression 4 \u00d7 100 metres freestyle relay]]\n* [[World record progression 4 \u00d7 100 metres medley relay]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Jason Lezak}}\n* {{USOC profile|LE/Jason-Lezak|name=Jason Lezak}}\n\n{{Footer USA Swimming 2000 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Footer USA Swimming 2004 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Footer USA Swimming 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Footer USA Swimming 2012 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Footer Olympic Champions 4x100 m Freestyle Relay Men}}\n{{Footer Olympic Champions 4x100 m Medley Relay Men}}\n{{Footer World LC Champions 4x100m Freestyle Men}}\n{{Footer World LC Champions 4x100m Medley Men}}\n{{Footer World SC Champions 100m Freestyle Men}}\n{{Footer World SC Champions 4x100m Freestyle Men}}\n{{Footer World SC Champions 4x100m Medley Men}}\n{{Footer Pan Pacific Champions 50m Freestyle Men}}\n{{Footer Pan Pacific Champions 4x100m Freestyle Men}}\n{{Footer Pan Pacific Champions 4x100m Medley Men}}\n{{Footer Universiade Champions 4x100m Freestyle Men}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lezak, Jason}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male freestyle swimmers]]\n[[Category:Jewish American sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Jewish swimmers]]\n[[Category:Maccabiah Games gold medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:Maccabiah Games medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for the United States in swimming]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for the United States in swimming]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for the United States in swimming]]\n[[Category:Olympic swimmers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Irvine, California]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2000 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2004 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:UC Santa Barbara Gauchos men's swimmers]]\n[[Category:World Aquatics Championships medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:World record holders in swimming]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2004 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2000 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2009 Maccabiah Games]]\n[[Category:Goodwill Games medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Universiade medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Universiade gold medalists for the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox swimmer\n| name           = Jason Lezak\n| image          = Jason Lezak 2.jpg\n| image_size     = 220\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Lezak at [[Maccabiah Games]] in July 2009\n| fullname       = Jason Edward Lezak\n| nicknames      = \n| national_team  = {{USA}}\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1975|11|12|mf=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Irvine, California]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = 6 ft 4 in\n| weight         = 210 lb\n| strokes        = [[Freestyle swimming|Freestyle]]\n| club           = [[Irvine Novaquatics]]<br />Rose Bowl Aquatics\n| collegeteam    = [[UC Santa Barbara Gau