{"title_page": "Chase Young", "text_new": "{{short description|American football defensive end}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{About|the American football player|the Xiaolin Showdown character|Chase Young (Xiaolin Showdown)}}\n<!-- DO NOT ADD BEFORE THE 2020 NFL DRAFT\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Chase Young\n| image               =\n| alt                 =\n| caption             =\n| number              = --\n| current_team        =\n| position            = [[Defensive end]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1999|4|14}}\n| birth_place         = [[Upper Marlboro, Maryland]]\n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 5\n| weight_lb           = 265\n| high_school         = [[DeMatha Catholic High School|DeMatha Catholic]] ([[Hyattsville, Maryland]])\n| college             = [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]]\n| draftyear           = 2020\n| draftround          =\n| draftpick           =\n| undraftedyear       =\n| pastteams           =\n* [[]] ({{NFL Year|2020}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Unsigned draft pick\n| highlights          =\n* [[Bronko Nagurski Trophy]] (2019)\n* [[Chuck Bednarik Award]] (2019)\n* [[Ted Hendricks Award]] (2019)\n* [[Chicago Tribune Silver Football]] (2019)\n* [[Nagurski\u2013Woodson Defensive Player of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Smith\u2013Brown Defensive Lineman of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Unanimous All-American]] ([[2019 College Football All-America Team|2019]])\n| statleague          = NFL\n| statseason          = 2020\n| statweek            =\n| statlabel1          = [[Tackle (football move)|Tackles]]\n| statvalue1          = 0\n| statlabel2          = [[Quarterback sack|Sacks]]\n| statvalue2          = 0\n| statlabel3          = [[Fumble|Forced fumbles]]\n| statvalue3          = 0\n| statlabel4          = [[Fumble|Fumble recoveries]]\n| statvalue4          = 0\n| nflnew              =\n| pfr                 = YounCh04\n}}\n-->\n{{Infobox college football player\n|name=Chase Young\n|school=Ohio State Buckeyes\n|currentnumber=2\n|major=[[Criminology]]\n|currentposition=[[Defensive end]]\n|class=Junior\n|bowlgames=\n* [[2017 Cotton Bowl Classic (December)]]\n* [[2019 Rose Bowl]]\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1999|4|14}}\n|birth_place=[[Upper Marlboro, Maryland]]\n|heightft=6\n|heightin=5\n|weight_lb=265\n|highschool=[[DeMatha Catholic High School|DeMatha Catholic]] ([[Hyattsville, Maryland]])\n|pastschools=\n* [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]] (2017\u20132019)\n|espn=4241986\n|highlights=\n* [[Bronko Nagurski Trophy]] (2019)\n* [[Chuck Bednarik Award]] (2019)\n* [[Ted Hendricks Award]] (2019)\n* [[Chicago Tribune Silver Football]] (2019)\n* [[Nagurski\u2013Woodson Defensive Player of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Smith\u2013Brown Defensive Lineman of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Unanimous All-American]] ([[2019 College Football All-America Team|2019]])\n* First-team All-Big Ten ([[2019 Big Ten Conference football season#All-Conference Teams|2019]])\n* Second-team All-Big Ten ([[2018 Big Ten Conference football season#All-Conference Teams|2018]])\n* Second-team ''USA Today'' High School All-American ([[2016 USA Today All-USA high school football team|2016]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[Walter Camp Award]] National Player of the Week\n}}\n'''Chase Young''' (born April 14, 1999) is an [[American football]] [[defensive end]]. He played college football at [[Ohio State University]], playing for the [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Buckeyes]] from 2017\u20132019. In his final season there, he broke the school's single-season sack record with 16.5, which won several honors such as the [[Bronko Nagurski Trophy]], [[Chuck Bednarik Award]], and [[Ted Hendricks Award]]. He was also named an [[unanimous All-American]] as well as a finalist for the [[Heisman Trophy]], a feat considered rare for a defensive player. He finished his career at Ohio State with 30.5 total sacks, which ranks second in school history.\n\n==Early life==\nChase Young was born in [[Upper Marlboro, Maryland]] on April 14, 1999.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chase Young Walter Camp National Defensive PoW \u2026 Again! |url=https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/chase-young-walter-camp-national-defensive-pow-again/ |website=OhioStateBuckeyes.com |accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref> He began playing American football as a child, later attending [[St. Vincent Pallotti High School]] in [[Laurel, Maryland]] as a freshman in 2013, where he started at [[quarterback]] and [[outside linebacker]] before switching to [[defensive end]] later that year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wiltfong |first1=Steve |title=The Chase for Young is on |url=https://247sports.com/Article/Touted-DE-Chase-Young-talks-Buckeyes-Maryland-Alabama-USC-44894899/ |website=[[247Sports.com]] |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704181213/http://247sports.com/Article/Touted-DE-Chase-Young-talks-Buckeyes-Maryland-Alabama-USC-44894899 |archive-date=July 4, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Santoliquito |first1=Joseph |title=Eagles fan Chase Young may soon become an Eagles\u2019 nightmare |url=https://www.phillyvoice.com/chase-young-philadelphia-eagles-fan-ohio-state-maxwell-awards-nfl-draft-washington-redskins/ |website=Philly Voice |accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> As a sophomore the following year, he and the team won the MIAA C conference championship.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Worgo |first1=Tom |title=Pallotti football relies on running game, defense to defeat AACS for MIAA C Conference title |url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/maryland/laurel/ph-ll-pallott-annapolisareachristianschool-footballi-story.html |website=Baltimore Sun |accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref> He was also a member of the school's choir, playing the piano, saxophone, and violin.<ref name=\"Dayton\">{{cite web |last1=Archdeacon |first1=Tom |title=Archdeacon: Ohio State\u2019s Young a menace in mauling of Badgers |url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/archdeacon-ohio-state-young-menace-mauling-badgers/U1tD5O9xjhQ7MBTEC9lc4J/ |website=Dayton Daily News |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029201708/https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/archdeacon-ohio-state-young-menace-mauling-badgers/U1tD5O9xjhQ7MBTEC9lc4J/ |archive-date=October 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he transferred to [[DeMatha Catholic High School]] in [[Hyattsville, Maryland]], where he had 19 sacks and 27 tackles for loss as a junior.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Parker |first1=Brandon |title=National Signing Day: A look ahead at Anthony McFarland, Deon Jones and the top Class of 2017 recruits |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/recruiting-insider/wp/2016/02/04/national-signing-day-a-look-ahead-at-anthony-mcfarland-deon-jones-and-the-top-class-of-2017-recruits/ |website=[[Washington Post]] |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> In July 2016, he was invited to The Opening, a college football recruiting camp.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Donohue |first1=Tyler |title=Highlights and Analysis from The Opening's Washington Regional |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2633644-highlights-and-analysis-from-the-opening-washington-dc-regional |website=Bleacher Report |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wiltfong |first1=Steve |title=Top Performers: The Opening Regional in Washington D.C. |url=https://247sports.com/Article/Top-Performers-The-Opening-Regional-in-Washington-DC-44867876/ |website=[[247Sports.com]] |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> As a senior in 2016, he had 19 sacks, 118 tackles, 5 forced fumbles, and 2 defensive touchdowns that helped the team go undefeated and win the state championship.<ref name=\"SeniorStats\">{{cite web |last1=Lind |first1=Andrew |title=The Hurry Up: Ohio State Makes Cut for Four-Star Texas Safety and Commit Caps High School Career With State Championship |url=https://www.elevenwarriors.com/ohio-state-football-recruiting/2016/12/78253/the-hurry-up-ohio-state-jordan-moore-top-10-wyatt-davis-state-championship |website=Eleven Warriors |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221202249/http://www.elevenwarriors.com/ohio-state-football-recruiting/2016/12/78253/the-hurry-up-ohio-state-jordan-moore-top-10-wyatt-davis-state-championship |archive-date=December 21, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"SportingNews\">{{cite web |last1=Bender |first1=Bill |title=The making of Chase Young: How an athletic freak at Ohio State became the best player in the NFL Draft |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/nfl/news/chase-young-ohio-state-best-player-nfl-draft/1bek45kwrzjmq12eh3jt0xre9g |website=Sporting News |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303052838/https://www.sportingnews.com/us/nfl/news/chase-young-ohio-state-best-player-nfl-draft/1bek45kwrzjmq12eh3jt0xre9g |archive-date=March 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was recognized one of the best high school football players in the nation, where he was included on the [[2016 USA Today All-USA high school football team]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Halley |first1=Jim |title=ALL-USA Football Defense: Second Team |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2016/2016-american-family-insurance-all-usa-football-defense-second-team |website=usatodayhss.com |publisher=USA Today |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202012103/http://usatodayhss.com/2016/2016-american-family-insurance-all-usa-football-defense-second-team |archive-date=February 2, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> as well as being named as the all-metropolitan defensive football player of the year by the ''[[Washington Post]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=2016 Fall All-Met |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/2016-fall-allmet/ |website=Washington Post |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626021033/https://www.washingtonpost.com/2016-fall-allmet/ |archive-date=June 26, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was also invited to the [[International Bowl presented by USA Football|International Bowl]] and [[All-American Bowl (high school football)|All-American Bowl]], playing on the East team for the latter.<ref name=\"SeniorStats\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=DeMatha defensive end Chase Young solidifies standing with Army All-American selection |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2016/dematha-defensive-end-chase-young-solidifies-standing-with-army-all-american-selection |website=usatodayhss.com |publisher=USA Today |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221142657/http://usatodayhss.com/2016/dematha-defensive-end-chase-young-solidifies-standing-with-army-all-american-selection/ |archive-date=December 21, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Young also played basketball for both schools, where he was a DeMatha teammate and friend of future [[NBA]] player [[Markelle Fultz]], who was [[List of first overall NBA draft picks|selected first overall]] in the [[2017 NBA Draft]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cadeaux |first1=Ethan |title=Markelle Fultz learned things the hard way so Chase Young won't have to |url=https://www.nbcsports.com/washington/redskins/markelle-fultz-learned-things-hard-way-so-chase-young-wont-have |website=NBCSports.com |publisher=NBC Sports Washington |accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nYoung received scholarship offers from over 40 colleges before committing to [[Ohio State University]] in July 2016, choosing them over other schools such as [[University of Alabama|Alabama]] and [[University of Maryland, College Park|Maryland]] due to the ability of Buckeyes defensive line coach [[Larry Johnson (American football coach)|Larry Johnson]], who personally recruited him, as well as the school's overall approach that he felt was more \"family-oriented\".<ref name=\"LarryJohnson\">{{cite web |last1=Stepien |first1=Garrett |title=Chase Young salutes Larry Johnson before Heisman ceremony |url=https://247sports.com/college/ohio-state/Article/Chase-Young-defensive-end-Ohio-State-Buckeyes-football-Larry-Johnson-position-coach-Heisman-Trophy-finalist-140532274/ |website=[[247Sports.com]] |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Connors |first1=Ryan |title=5-star DE Chase Young commits to Ohio State: Maryland football misses out on top local prospect |url=https://www.testudotimes.com/2016/7/22/12261298/maryland-football-recruiting-chase-young-commits-ohio-state |website=testudotimes.com |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030181151/http://www.testudotimes.com/2016/7/22/12261298/maryland-football-recruiting-chase-young-commits-ohio-state |archive-date=October 30, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lombardi |first1=Matt |title=Chase Young Explains Why He Chose Ohio State Over Alabama |url=https://thespun.com/big-ten/ohio-state-buckeyes/chase-young-explains-why-he-chose-ohio-state-over-alabama |website=The Spun |accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref> As a freshman in 2017, Young recorded 3.5 sacks, 18 tackles, and a forced fumble as a rotational player.<ref name=\"LarryJohnson\"/><ref name=\"Sophomore\">{{cite web |last1=Ludwiczak |first1=Brett |title=Ohio State defensive end Chase Young is ready to build off a breakout sophomore season |url=https://www.landgrantholyland.com/2019/1/17/18186858/ohio-state-news-football-chase-young-jonathon-cooper-zach-harrison-womens-basketball-kevin-mcguff |website=Land Grant Holy Land |accessdate=May 10, 2019 |date=January 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510191344/https://www.landgrantholyland.com/2019/1/17/18186858/ohio-state-news-football-chase-young-jonathon-cooper-zach-harrison-womens-basketball-kevin-mcguff |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The following season, Young recorded 10.5 sacks despite spraining both ankles midway through the season.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Haas-Hill |first1=Colin |title=K.J. Hill, Chase Young and J.K. Dobbins Could Break or Tie Ohio State Individual Records in 2019 |url=https://www.elevenwarriors.com/ohio-state-football/2019/05/104153/ohio-state-individual-records-in-jeopardy-of-being-broken-next-season |website=Eleven Warriors |accessdate=May 10, 2019 |date=May 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510191351/https://www.elevenwarriors.com/ohio-state-football/2019/05/104153/ohio-state-individual-records-in-jeopardy-of-being-broken-next-season |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He began to play more after fellow defensive end [[Nick Bosa]] was injured in the latter part of the season, recording three sacks in the [[2018 Big Ten Football Championship Game]] against [[Northwestern Wildcats football|Northwestern]].<ref name=\"Sophomore\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rowland |first1=Kyle |title=Ohio State defensive end Chase Young wants to be the best |url=https://www.toledoblade.com/sports/ohio-state/2018/10/10/ohio-state-buckeyes-football-chase-young-wants-to-be-the-best/stories/20181009108 |website=[[Toledo Blade]] |accessdate=May 10, 2019 |date=October 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510205559/https://www.toledoblade.com/sports/ohio-state/2018/10/10/ohio-state-buckeyes-football-chase-young-wants-to-be-the-best/stories/20181009108 |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was named to the second-team All-Big Ten team for the season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Big Ten Announces Football All-Conference Teams for Defense and Special Teams and Select Individual Honors |url=https://bigten.org/news/2018/11/27/big-ten-announces-football-all-conference-teams-for-defense-and-special-teams-and-select-individual-honors.aspx |website=BigTen.org |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring his junior season in 2019, Young tied Ohio State school records for single-game sacks (4) and tackles for loss (5) in a win against [[Wisconsin Badgers football|Wisconsin]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Planos |first1=Josh |title=Ohio State's Chase Young Is Playing Like A Heisman Contender |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/ohio-states-chase-young-is-playing-like-a-heisman-contender/ |website=FiveThirtyEight |publisher=ABC News Internet Ventures |accessdate=November 14, 2019 |date=October 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116060500/https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/ohio-states-chase-young-is-playing-like-a-heisman-contender/ |archive-date=November 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Heisman Watch: Chase Young Crashes Quarterback Party |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/page/HeismanWatch191029/heisman-watch-chase-young-crashes-quarterback-party |website=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=November 14, 2019 |date=October 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191031175718/https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/page/HeismanWatch191029/heisman-watch-chase-young-crashes-quarterback-party |archive-date=October 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hummer |first1=Chris |title=Chase Young is on a historic, Heisman-worthy pace |url=https://247sports.com/college/ohio-state/Article/Chase-Young-Heisman-Trophy-Ohio-State-football-2020-NFL-Draft-137613670/ |website=[[247Sports.com]] |accessdate=November 14, 2019 |date=October 28, 2019}}</ref> In November 2019, Young was suspended for two games by the [[NCAA]] for getting an unauthorized loan from a family friend to allegedly help his girlfriend attend the [[2019 Rose Bowl]], which he later repaid in full.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bumbaca |first1=Chris |title=Ohio State Buckeyes' Chase Young expected to serve four-game suspension, per reports |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/bigten/2019/11/09/chase-young-suspension-ohio-state-expects-heisman-out-4-games/2543764001/ |website=USA Today |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408013511/https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/bigten/2019/11/09/chase-young-suspension-ohio-state-expects-heisman-out-4-games/2543764001/ |archive-date=April 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Shook |first1=Nick |title=NCAA rules Ohio State's Chase Young to miss 1 more game |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001076478/article/ncaa-rules-ohio-states-chase-young-to-miss-1-more-game |website=NFL.com |accessdate=November 13, 2019 |date=November 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113185829/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001076478/article/ncaa-rules-ohio-states-chase-young-to-miss-1-more-game |archive-date=November 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Young recorded three sacks against Penn State in his first game after returning.<ref name=\"SportingNews\"/> He ended the season with 16.5 sacks, 46 tackles, 21 tackles for loss, 7 forced fumbles, 3 passes batted down, and a blocked field goal.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rapp |first1=Timothy |title=Chase Young Rumors: Teams Behind Lions in 2020 NFL Draft Haven't Contacted Star |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2885639-chase-young-rumors-teams-behind-lions-in-2020-nfl-draft-havent-contacted-star |website=Bleacher Report |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Noga |first1=Joe |title=Chase Young, Ohio State DE: 2020 NFL Draft profile |url=https://www.cleveland.com/browns/2020/03/chase-young-ohio-state-de-2020-nfl-draft-profile.html |website=Cleveland.com |access-date=March 10, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331014816/https://www.cleveland.com/browns/2020/03/chase-young-ohio-state-de-2020-nfl-draft-profile.html |archive-date=March 31, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> His 16.5 sacks broke the single-season school record previously held by [[Vernon Gholston]], who had 14 in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kaufman |first1=Joey |title=Chase Young a Heisman finalist despite playing defense, being suspended |url=https://www.buckeyextra.com/sports/20191213/ohio-state-football--chase-young-heisman-finalist-despite-playing-defense-being-suspended |website=Buckeyextra.com |publisher=The Columbus Dispatch |accessdate=December 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191224230059/https://www.buckeyextra.com/sports/20191213/ohio-state-football--chase-young-heisman-finalist-despite-playing-defense-being-suspended |archive-date=December 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nYoung won several awards and honors for his performance that season, including the [[Bronko Nagurski Trophy]],<ref name=\"Bronko\">{{cite web |last1=Straka |first1=Dean |title=Ohio State DE Chase Young wins Bronko Nagurski Trophy |url=https://247sports.com/Article/ohio-state-defensive-end-chase-young-wins-2019-bronko-nagurski-trophy-140221610/ |website=[[247Sports.com]] |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref> [[Chuck Bednarik Award]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Chase Young Wins 2019 Chuck Bednarik Award |url=https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/chase-young-wins-2019-bednarik-award/ |website=OhioStateBuckeyes.com |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103195746/https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/chase-young-wins-2019-bednarik-award/ |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Ted Hendricks Award]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clay |first1=Jarrod |title=Chase Young wins 2019 Ted Hendricks Award |url=https://abc6onyourside.com/sports/the-football-fever/chase-young-wins-2019-ted-hendricks-award |website=ABC 6 |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103195619/https://abc6onyourside.com/sports/the-football-fever/chase-young-wins-2019-ted-hendricks-award |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Chicago Tribune Silver Football]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greenstein |first1=Teddy |title=Chase Young is the 2019 Chicago Tribune Silver Football winner \u2014 and the 1st Ohio State defensive player to win the award in its 95-year history |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/college/ct-chase-young-ohio-state-silver-football-20191206-imh2o6cs45cpdbj5e7b7sla4zu-story.html |website=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230142145/https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/college/ct-chase-young-ohio-state-silver-football-20191206-imh2o6cs45cpdbj5e7b7sla4zu-story.html |archive-date=December 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Nagurski\u2013Woodson Defensive Player of the Year]],<ref name=\"Bronko\"/> and [[Smith\u2013Brown Defensive Lineman of the Year]].<ref name=\"Bronko\"/> In addition, he was twice named the [[Walter Camp Award|Walter Camp]] defensive player of the week for his performances against Wisconsin and Penn State,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hass-Hill |first1=Colin |title=Chase Young Named Walter Camp National Defensive Player Of The Week For Second Time This Season |url=https://www.elevenwarriors.com/ohio-state-football/2019/11/109337/chase-young-named-walter-camp-national-defensive-player-of-the-week-for-second-time-this-season |website=Elevan Warriors |accessdate=March 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127222424/https://www.elevenwarriors.com/ohio-state-football/2019/11/109337/chase-young-named-walter-camp-national-defensive-player-of-the-week-for-second-time-this-season |archive-date=November 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and was [[List of unanimous All-Americans in college football|unanimously named]] to the 2019 All-Big Ten and [[2019 College Football All-America Team|All-America Teams]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Big Ten Announces Football All-Conference Teams for Defense and Special Teams and Select Individual Honors |url=https://bigten.org/news/2019/12/3/big-ten-announces-football-all-conference-teams-for-defense-and-special-teams-and-select-individual-honors.aspx |website=BigTen.org |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204022652/https://bigten.org/news/2019/12/3/big-ten-announces-football-all-conference-teams-for-defense-and-special-teams-and-select-individual-honors.aspx |archive-date=December 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was also named a finalist for the [[Walter Camp Award]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rosvoglou |first1=Chris |title=5 Finalists Announced For Walter Camp Player Of The Year |url=https://thespun.com/big-ten/ohio-state-buckeyes/finalists-announced-for-walter-camp-player-of-the-year |website=The Spun |accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> [[Maxwell Award]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Duffley |first1=John |title=Joe Burrow Wins Maxwell Award as CFB\u2019s Player of the Year |url=https://fanbuzz.com/college-football/maxwell-award-watch-list/ |website=FanBuzz.com |accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref> and [[Heisman Trophy]], becoming only the ninth defensive player since 1982 to be nominated for the latter, where he finished fourth in voting behind quarterbacks [[Joe Burrow]], [[Jalen Hurts]], and [[Justin Fields]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cross |first1=Ian |title=OSU defensive end Chase Young declares for 2020 NFL Draft |url=https://www.news5cleveland.com/sports/college-sports/osu/osu-defensive-end-chase-young-declares-for-2020-nfl-draft |website=News 5 Cleveland |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104141151/https://www.news5cleveland.com/sports/college-sports/osu/osu-defensive-end-chase-young-declares-for-2020-nfl-draft |archive-date=January 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author1=ESPN News Services |title=Bayou bliss: LSU QB Joe Burrow takes home Heisman |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/28298763/bayou-bliss-lsu-qb-joe-burrow-takes-home-heisman |website=ESPN |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230123538/https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/28298763/bayou-bliss-lsu-qb-joe-burrow-takes-home-heisman |archive-date=December 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He finished his career at Ohio State with 30.5 total sacks, which ranks second all-time there behind [[Mike Vrabel]]'s 36.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anders |first1=Andy |title=Football: Chase Young declares for NFL Draft |url=https://www.thelantern.com/2020/01/ohio-state-football-chase-young-declares-for-nfl-draft-2/ |website=The Latern |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406225649/https://www.thelantern.com/2020/01/ohio-state-football-chase-young-declares-for-nfl-draft-2/ |archive-date=April 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2|Season\n! colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"2\" |Games\n! colspan=4|Tackles\n! colspan=2|Sacks\n! colspan=2|Fumbles\n|-\n! Solo !! Ast !! Total !! TFL !! Total !! Yards\n!FF\n!FR\n|-\n![[2017 Ohio State Buckeyes football season|2017]]\n|9\n|11\n|7\n|18\n|5\n|3.5\n|20\n|1\n| rowspan=\"3\" |0\n|-\n![[2018 Ohio State Buckeyes football season|2018]]\n|13\n|25\n|9\n|34\n|14.5\n|10.5\n|60\n|1\n|-\n![[2019 Ohio State Buckeyes football season|2019]]\n|12\n|32\n|14\n|46\n|21\n|16.5\n|117\n|7\n|-\n! Totals<ref>{{cite web |title=Chase Young College Stats |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/chase-young-1.html |website=sports-reference.com |publisher=College Football Reference |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408093051/https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/chase-young-1.html |archive-date=April 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n!34\n!68||30||98||40.5||30.5||197\n!9\n!0\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nYoung decided to forgo his senior year at Ohio State by declaring for the [[2020 NFL Draft]],<ref>{{cite web |author1=ESPN |title=Ohio State DE Chase Young announces he's entering NFL draft |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/28416265/ohio-state-de-chase-young-announces-entering-nfl-draft |website=ESPN |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103191232/https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/28416265/ohio-state-de-chase-young-announces-entering-nfl-draft |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Shook |first1=Nick |title=Ohio State DE Chase Young declares for 2020 draft |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001094141/article/ohio-state-de-chase-young-declares-for-2020-draft |website=NFL.com |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103195556/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001094141/article/ohio-state-de-chase-young-declares-for-2020-draft |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> where he is considered by many to be its best overall prospect.<ref name=\"SportingNews\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Birkett |first1=Dave |title=Chase Young is NFL draft's No. 1 prospect; don't let late-season slump worry you |url=https://www.freep.com/story/sports/nfl/lions/2020/02/24/chase-young-ohio-state-football-nfl-draft/4856539002/ |website=Detroit Free Press |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225215049/https://www.freep.com/story/sports/nfl/lions/2020/02/24/chase-young-ohio-state-football-nfl-draft/4856539002/ |archive-date=February 25, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=McAtee |first1=Riley |title=Chase Young and the Perennial Draft Appeal of an Elite Pass Rusher |url=https://www.theringer.com/nfl/2020/4/13/21218550/2020-nfl-draft-chase-young-defensive-end-prospects-trend |website=[[The Ringer]] |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> He attended the [[NFL Combine]] but did not participate in any workouts or drills, stating that he did not want to waste time being a \"combine athlete\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=DelVecchio |first1=Steve |title=Chase Young has great explanation for skipping combine workouts |url=https://www.yardbarker.com/nfl/articles/chase_young_has_great_explanation_for_skipping_combine_workouts/s1_127_31450310 |website=[[Yardbarker]] |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303053338/https://www.yardbarker.com/nfl/articles/chase_young_has_great_explanation_for_skipping_combine_workouts/s1_127_31450310 |archive-date=March 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Young was one of 58 players invited to the draft, which is to be held virtually due to [[social distancing]] regulations arising from the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |author1=Around The NFL staff |title=58 prospects to virtually participate in NFL draft |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001108866/article/58-prospects-to-virtually-participate-in-nfl-draft |website=NFL.com |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200410064948/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001108866/article/58-prospects-to-virtually-participate-in-nfl-draft |archive-date=April 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nYoung's father, Greg, played college basketball at [[Bowie State University]] before working as a police deputy with the [[Arlington County Sheriff's Office]], while his mother, Carla, works for the [[Office of Investigations for the Department of Transportation]].<ref name=\"Dayton\"/><ref name=\"Law\">{{cite web |last1=Means |first1=Stephen |title=Ohio State\u2019s star DE Chase Young following his family\u2019s formula to success: From athletics to law enforcement |url=https://www.cleveland.com/osu/2019/09/ohio-states-star-de-chase-young-following-his-familys-formula-to-success-from-athletics-to-law-enforcement.html |website=Cleveland.com |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191003205731/https://www.cleveland.com/osu/2019/09/ohio-states-star-de-chase-young-following-his-familys-formula-to-success-from-athletics-to-law-enforcement.html |archive-date=October 3, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"2PointStance\">{{cite web |last1=Goodbread |first1=Chase |title=Two-Point Stance |url=http://www.nfl.com/labs/cfb247/chase-young/chase-young |website=NFL.com |accessdate=April 16, 2020 |date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Young has a sister, Weslie, who played college basketball at [[North Carolina Wesleyan]].<ref name=\"Tattoo\">{{cite web |last1=Culpepper |first1=Chuck |title=A veteran and grandfather\u2019s kinetic tribute \u2014 on the arm of college football\u2019s best player |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/11/22/chase-young-grandfather-tattoo-nfl-ohio-state-college-football/ |website=[[Washington Post]] |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229110140/https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/11/22/chase-young-grandfather-tattoo-nfl-ohio-state-college-football/ |archive-date=December 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> At Ohio State, Young pursued a [[major (academics)|major]] in [[criminology]] after being inspired by his father and several of his uncles and cousins, who all work in [[law enforcement]].<ref name=\"Law\"/><ref name=\"2PointStance\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Chase Young, DeMatha Catholic, Weak-Side Defensive End |url=https://247sports.com/Player/Chase-Young-83154/high-school-144085/ |website=[[247Sports.com]] |accessdate=May 10, 2019}}</ref> He is sometimes called the \"Predator\" for his on-field dominance, as well as his [[dreadlock]]s resembling [[Predator (fictional species)|Predators]] from the ''[[Predator (franchise)|Predator]]'' franchise.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thamel |first1=Pete |title=Why freaky OSU DE Chase Young is the best player in college football: \u2018There\u2019s only 10 guys like him in the world\u2019 |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/chase-young-best-player-in-college-football-154802867.html |website=sports.yahoo.com |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101104924/https://sports.yahoo.com/chase-young-best-player-in-college-football-154802867.html |archive-date=January 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hooley |first1=Bruce |title=Jackson Carman Eluded Ohio State; will Block Chase Young |url=https://www.si.com/college/ohiostate/football/jackson-carman-eluded-ohio-state-now-will-block-chase-young |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225151946/https://www.si.com/college/ohiostate/football/jackson-carman-eluded-ohio-state-now-will-block-chase-young |archive-date=December 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hooley |first1=Bruce |title=Ohio State's Chase Young May Be Better Than Bosa Brothers |url=https://www.si.com/college/ohiostate/football/ohio-states-chase-young-may-be-better-than-bosa-brothers |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Young has a tattoo of Carl H. Robinson, his late grandfather and [[US Air Force]] veteran, on his right arm.<ref name=\"Tattoo\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{twitter|youngchase907}}\n* [https://www.nfl.com/prospects/chase-young?id=3219594f-5514-6550-d662-263c81d981b1 NFL.com prospect profile]\n* [http://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/roster/chase-young/ Ohio State Buckeyes bio]\n\n{{Navboxes|title=Chase Young|list=\n{{Bronko Nagurski Trophy}}\n{{Chuck Bednarik Award}}\n{{Ted Hendricks Award}}\n{{Chicago Tribune Silver Football navbox}}\n{{2019 NCAA Division I FBS College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Young, Chase}}\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:American football defensive ends]]\n[[Category:DeMatha Catholic High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ohio State Buckeyes football players]]\n[[Category:People from Upper Marlboro, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from the Washington metropolitan area]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football defensive end}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{About|the American football player|the Xiaolin Showdown character|Chase Young (Xiaolin Showdown)}}\n<!-- DO NOT ADD BEFORE THE 2020 NFL DRAFT\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Chase Young\n| image               =\n| alt                 =\n| caption             =\n| number              = --\n| current_team        =\n| position            = [[Defensive end]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1999|4|14}}\n| birth_place         = [[Upper Marlboro, Maryland]]\n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 5\n| weight_lb           = 265\n| high_school         = [[DeMatha Catholic High School|DeMatha Catholic]] ([[Hyattsville, Maryland]])\n| college             = [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]]\n| draftyear           = 2020\n| draftround          =\n| draftpick           =\n| undraftedyear       =\n| pastteams           =\n* [[]] ({{NFL Year|2020}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Unsigned draft pick\n| highlights          =\n* [[Bronko Nagurski Trophy]] (2019)\n* [[Chuck Bednarik Award]] (2019)\n* [[Ted Hendricks Award]] (2019)\n* [[Chicago Tribune Silver Football]] (2019)\n* [[Nagurski\u2013Woodson Defensive Player of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Smith\u2013Brown Defensive Lineman of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Unanimous All-American]] ([[2019 College Football All-America Team|2019]])\n| statleague          = NFL\n| statseason          =\n| statweek            =\n| statlabel1          = [[Tackle (football move)|Tackles]]\n| statvalue1          = 0\n| statlabel2          = [[Quarterback sack|Sacks]]\n| statvalue2          = 0\n| statlabel3          = [[Fumble|Forced fumbles]]\n| statvalue3          = 0\n| statlabel4          = [[Fumble|Fumble recoveries]]\n| statvalue4          = 0\n| nflnew              =\n| pfr                 = YounCh04\n}}\n-->\n{{Infobox college football player\n|name=Chase Young\n|school=Ohio State Buckeyes\n|currentnumber=2\n|major=[[Criminology]]\n|currentposition=[[Defensive end]]\n|class=Junior\n|bowlgames=\n* [[2017 Cotton Bowl Classic (December)]]\n* [[2019 Rose Bowl]]\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1999|4|14}}\n|birth_place=[[Upper Marlboro, Maryland]]\n|heightft=6\n|heightin=5\n|weight_lb=265\n|highschool=[[DeMatha Catholic High School|DeMatha Catholic]] ([[Hyattsville, Maryland]])\n|pastschools=\n* [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]] (2017\u20132019)\n|espn=4241986\n|highlights=\n* [[Bronko Nagurski Trophy]] (2019)\n* [[Chuck Bednarik Award]] (2019)\n* [[Ted Hendricks Award]] (2019)\n* [[Chicago Tribune Silver Football]] (2019)\n* [[Nagurski\u2013Woodson Defensive Player of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Smith\u2013Brown Defensive Lineman of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[Unanimous All-American]] ([[2019 College Football All-America Team|2019]])\n* First-team All-Big Ten ([[2019 Big Ten Conference football season#All-Conference Teams|2019]])\n* Second-team All-Big Ten ([[2018 Big Ten Conference football season#All-Conference Teams|2018]])\n* Second-team ''USA Today'' High School All-American ([[2016 USA Today All-USA high school football team|2016]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[Walter Camp Award]] National Player of the Week\n}}\n'''Chase Young''' (born April 14, 1999) is an [[American football]] [[defensive end]]. He played college football at [[Ohio State University]], playing for the [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Buckeyes]] from 2017\u20132019. In his final season there, he broke the school's single-season sack record with 16.5, which won several honors such as the [[Bronko Nagurski Trophy]], [[Chuck Bednarik Award]], and [[Ted Hendricks Award]]. He was also named an [[unanimous All-American]] as well as a finalist for the [[Heisman Trophy]], a feat considered rare for a defensive player. He finished his career at Ohio State with 30.5 total sacks, which ranks second in school history.\n\n==Early life==\nChase Young was born in [[Upper Marlboro, Maryland]] on April 14, 1999.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chase Young Walter Camp National Defensive PoW \u2026 Again! |url=https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/chase-young-walter-camp-national-defensive-pow-again/ |website=OhioStateBuckeyes.com |accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref> He began playing American football as a child, later attending [[St. Vincent Pallotti High School]] in [[Laurel, Maryland]] as a freshman in 2013, where he started at [[quarterback]] and [[outside linebacker]] before switching to defensive end later that year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wiltfong |first1=Steve |title=The Chase for Young is on |url=https://247sports.com/Article/Touted-DE-Chase-Young-talks-Buckeyes-Maryland-Alabama-USC-44894899/ |website=[[247Sports.com]] |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704181213/http://247sports.com/Article/Touted-DE-Chase-Young-talks-Buckeyes-Maryland-Alabama-USC-44894899 |archive-date=July 4, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Santoliquito |first1=Joseph |title=Eagles fan Chase Young may soon become an Eagles\u2019 nightmare |url=https://www.phillyvoice.com/chase-young-philadelphia-eagles-fan-ohio-state-maxwell-awards-nfl-draft-washington-redskins/ |website=Philly Voice |accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> As a sophomore the following year, he and the team won the MIAA C conference championship.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Worgo |first1=Tom |title=Pallotti football relies on running game, defense to defeat AACS for MIAA C Conference title |url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/maryland/laurel/ph-ll-pallott-annapolisareachristianschool-footballi-story.html |website=Baltimore Sun |accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref> He was also a member of the school's choir, playing the piano, saxophone, and violin.<ref name=\"Dayton\">{{cite web |last1=Archdeacon |first1=Tom |title=Archdeacon: Ohio State\u2019s Young a menace in mauling of Badgers |url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/archdeacon-ohio-state-young-menace-mauling-badgers/U1tD5O9xjhQ7MBTEC9lc4J/ |website=Dayton Daily News |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029201708/https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/archdeacon-ohio-state-young-menace-mauling-badgers/U1tD5O9xjhQ7MBTEC9lc4J/ |archive-date=October 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he transferred to [[DeMatha Catholic High School]] in [[Hyattsville, Maryland]], where he had 19 sacks and 27 tackles for loss as a junior.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Parker |first1=Brandon |title=National Signing Day: A look ahead at Anthony McFarland, Deon Jones and the top Class of 2017 recruits |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/recruiting-insider/wp/2016/02/04/national-signing-day-a-look-ahead-at-anthony-mcfarland-deon-jones-and-the-top-class-of-2017-recruits/ |website=[[Washington Post]] |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> In July 2016, he was invited to The Opening, a college football recruiting camp.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Donohue |first1=Tyler |title=Highlights and Analysis from The Opening's Washington Regional |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2633644-highlights-and-analysis-from-the-opening-washington-dc-regional |website=Bleacher Report |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wiltfong |first1=Steve |title=Top Performers: The Opening Regional in Washington D.C. |url=https://247sports.com/Article/Top-Performers-The-Opening-Regional-in-Washington-DC-44867876/ |website=[[247Sports.com]] |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> As a senior in 2016, he had 19 sacks, 118 tackles, 5 forced fumbles, and 2 defensive touchdowns that helped the team go undefeated and win the state championship.<ref name=\"SeniorStats\">{{cite web |last1=Lind |first1=Andrew |title=The Hurry Up: Ohio State Makes Cut for Four-Star Texas Safety and Commit Caps High School Career With State Championship |url=https://www.elevenwarriors.com/ohio-state-football-recruiting/2016/12/78253/the-hurry-up-ohio-state-jordan-moore-top-10-wyatt-davis-state-championship |website=Eleven Warriors |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221202249/http://www.elevenwarriors.com/ohio-state-football-recruiting/2016/12/78253/the-hurry-up-ohio-state-jordan-moore-top-10-wyatt-davis-state-championship |archive-date=December 21, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"SportingNews\">{{cite web |last1=Bender |first1=Bill |title=The making of Chase Young: How an athletic freak at Ohio State became the best player in the NFL Draft |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/nfl/news/chase-young-ohio-state-best-player-nfl-draft/1bek45kwrzjmq12eh3jt0xre9g |website=Sporting News |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303052838/https://www.sportingnews.com/us/nfl/news/chase-young-ohio-state-best-player-nfl-draft/1bek45kwrzjmq12eh3jt0xre9g |archive-date=March 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was recognized one of the best high school football players in the nation, where he was included on the [[2016 USA Today All-USA high school football team]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Halley |first1=Jim |title=ALL-USA Football Defense: Second Team |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2016/2016-american-family-insurance-all-usa-football-defense-second-team |website=usatodayhss.com |publisher=USA Today |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202012103/http://usatodayhss.com/2016/2016-american-family-insurance-all-usa-football-defense-second-team |archive-date=February 2, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> as well as being named as the all-metropolitan defensive football player of the year by the ''[[Washington Post]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=2016 Fall All-Met |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/2016-fall-allmet/ |website=Washington Post |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626021033/https://www.washingtonpost.com/2016-fall-allmet/ |archive-date=June 26, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was also invited to the [[International Bowl presented by USA Football|International Bowl]] and [[All-American Bowl (high school football)|All-American Bowl]], playing on the East team for the latter.<ref name=\"SeniorStats\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=DeMatha defensive end Chase Young solidifies standing with Army All-American selection |url=https://usatodayhss.com/2016/dematha-defensive-end-chase-young-solidifies-standing-with-army-all-american-selection |website=usatodayhss.com |publisher=USA Today |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221142657/http://usatodayhss.com/2016/dematha-defensive-end-chase-young-solidifies-standing-with-army-all-american-selection/ |archive-date=December 21, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Young also played basketball for both schools, where he was a DeMatha teammate and friend of future [[NBA]] player [[Markelle Fultz]], who was [[List of first overall NBA draft picks|selected first overall]] in the [[2017 NBA Draft]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cadeaux |first1=Ethan |title=Markelle Fultz learned things the hard way so Chase Young won't have to |url=https://www.nbcsports.com/washington/redskins/markelle-fultz-learned-things-hard-way-so-chase-young-wont-have |website=NBCSports.com |publisher=NBC Sports Washington |accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nYoung received scholarship offers from over 40 colleges before committing to [[Ohio State University]] in July 2016, choosing them over other schools such as [[University of Alabama|Alabama]] and [[University of Maryland, College Park|Maryland]] due to the ability of Buckeyes defensive line coach [[Larry Johnson (American football coach)|Larry Johnson]], who personally recruited him, as well as the school's overall approach that he felt was more \"family-oriented\".<ref name=\"LarryJohnson\">{{cite web |last1=Stepien |first1=Garrett |title=Chase Young salutes Larry Johnson before Heisman ceremony |url=https://247sports.com/college/ohio-state/Article/Chase-Young-defensive-end-Ohio-State-Buckeyes-football-Larry-Johnson-position-coach-Heisman-Trophy-finalist-140532274/ |website=[[247Sports.com]] |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Connors |first1=Ryan |title=5-star DE Chase Young commits to Ohio State: Maryland football misses out on top local prospect |url=https://www.testudotimes.com/2016/7/22/12261298/maryland-football-recruiting-chase-young-commits-ohio-state |website=testudotimes.com |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030181151/http://www.testudotimes.com/2016/7/22/12261298/maryland-football-recruiting-chase-young-commits-ohio-state |archive-date=October 30, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lombardi |first1=Matt |title=Chase Young Explains Why He Chose Ohio State Over Alabama |url=https://thespun.com/big-ten/ohio-state-buckeyes/chase-young-explains-why-he-chose-ohio-state-over-alabama |website=The Spun |accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref> As a freshman in 2017, Young recorded 3.5 sacks, 18 tackles, and a forced fumble as a rotational player.<ref name=\"LarryJohnson\"/><ref name=\"Sophomore\">{{cite web |last1=Ludwiczak |first1=Brett |title=Ohio State defensive end Chase Young is ready to build off a breakout sophomore season |url=https://www.landgrantholyland.com/2019/1/17/18186858/ohio-state-news-football-chase-young-jonathon-cooper-zach-harrison-womens-basketball-kevin-mcguff |website=Land Grant Holy Land |accessdate=May 10, 2019 |date=January 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510191344/https://www.landgrantholyland.com/2019/1/17/18186858/ohio-state-news-football-chase-young-jonathon-cooper-zach-harrison-womens-basketball-kevin-mcguff |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The following season, Young recorded 10.5 sacks despite spraining both ankles midway through the season.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Haas-Hill |first1=Colin |title=K.J. Hill, Chase Young and J.K. Dobbins Could Break or Tie Ohio State Individual Records in 2019 |url=https://www.elevenwarriors.com/ohio-state-football/2019/05/104153/ohio-state-individual-records-in-jeopardy-of-being-broken-next-season |website=Eleven Warriors |accessdate=May 10, 2019 |date=May 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510191351/https://www.elevenwarriors.com/ohio-state-football/2019/05/104153/ohio-state-individual-records-in-jeopardy-of-being-broken-next-season |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He began to play more after fellow defensive end [[Nick Bosa]] was injured in the latter part of the season, recording three sacks in the [[2018 Big Ten Football Championship Game]] against [[Northwestern Wildcats football|Northwestern]].<ref name=\"Sophomore\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rowland |first1=Kyle |title=Ohio State defensive end Chase Young wants to be the best |url=https://www.toledoblade.com/sports/ohio-state/2018/10/10/ohio-state-buckeyes-football-chase-young-wants-to-be-the-best/stories/20181009108 |website=[[Toledo Blade]] |accessdate=May 10, 2019 |date=October 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510205559/https://www.toledoblade.com/sports/ohio-state/2018/10/10/ohio-state-buckeyes-football-chase-young-wants-to-be-the-best/stories/20181009108 |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was named to the second-team All-Big Ten team for the season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Big Ten Announces Football All-Conference Teams for Defense and Special Teams and Select Individual Honors |url=https://bigten.org/news/2018/11/27/big-ten-announces-football-all-conference-teams-for-defense-and-special-teams-and-select-individual-honors.aspx |website=BigTen.org |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring his junior season in 2019, Young tied Ohio State school records for single-game sacks (4) and tackles for loss (5) in a win against [[Wisconsin Badgers football|Wisconsin]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Planos |first1=Josh |title=Ohio State's Chase Young Is Playing Like A Heisman Contender |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/ohio-states-chase-young-is-playing-like-a-heisman-contender/ |website=FiveThirtyEight |publisher=ABC News Internet Ventures |accessdate=November 14, 2019 |date=October 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116060500/https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/ohio-states-chase-young-is-playing-like-a-heisman-contender/ |archive-date=November 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Heisman Watch: Chase Young Crashes Quarterback Party |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/page/HeismanWatch191029/heisman-watch-chase-young-crashes-quarterback-party |website=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=November 14, 2019 |date=October 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191031175718/https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/page/HeismanWatch191029/heisman-watch-chase-young-crashes-quarterback-party |archive-date=October 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hummer |first1=Chris |title=Chase Young is on a historic, Heisman-worthy pace |url=https://247sports.com/college/ohio-state/Article/Chase-Young-Heisman-Trophy-Ohio-State-football-2020-NFL-Draft-137613670/ |website=[[247Sports.com]] |accessdate=November 14, 2019 |date=October 28, 2019}}</ref> In November 2019, Young was suspended for two games by the [[NCAA]] for getting an unauthorized loan from a family friend to allegedly help his girlfriend attend the [[2019 Rose Bowl]], which he later repaid in full.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bumbaca |first1=Chris |title=Ohio State Buckeyes' Chase Young expected to serve four-game suspension, per reports |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/bigten/2019/11/09/chase-young-suspension-ohio-state-expects-heisman-out-4-games/2543764001/ |website=USA Today |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408013511/https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/bigten/2019/11/09/chase-young-suspension-ohio-state-expects-heisman-out-4-games/2543764001/ |archive-date=April 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Shook |first1=Nick |title=NCAA rules Ohio State's Chase Young to miss 1 more game |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001076478/article/ncaa-rules-ohio-states-chase-young-to-miss-1-more-game |website=NFL.com |accessdate=November 13, 2019 |date=November 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113185829/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001076478/article/ncaa-rules-ohio-states-chase-young-to-miss-1-more-game |archive-date=November 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Young recorded three sacks against Penn State in his first game after returning.<ref name=\"SportingNews\"/> He ended the season with 16.5 sacks, 46 tackles, 21 tackles for loss, 7 forced fumbles, 3 passes batted down, and a blocked field goal.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rapp |first1=Timothy |title=Chase Young Rumors: Teams Behind Lions in 2020 NFL Draft Haven't Contacted Star |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2885639-chase-young-rumors-teams-behind-lions-in-2020-nfl-draft-havent-contacted-star |website=Bleacher Report |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Noga |first1=Joe |title=Chase Young, Ohio State DE: 2020 NFL Draft profile |url=https://www.cleveland.com/browns/2020/03/chase-young-ohio-state-de-2020-nfl-draft-profile.html |website=Cleveland.com |access-date=March 10, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331014816/https://www.cleveland.com/browns/2020/03/chase-young-ohio-state-de-2020-nfl-draft-profile.html |archive-date=March 31, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> His 16.5 sacks broke the single-season school record previously held by [[Vernon Gholston]], who had 14 in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kaufman |first1=Joey |title=Chase Young a Heisman finalist despite playing defense, being suspended |url=https://www.buckeyextra.com/sports/20191213/ohio-state-football--chase-young-heisman-finalist-despite-playing-defense-being-suspended |website=Buckeyextra.com |publisher=The Columbus Dispatch |accessdate=December 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191224230059/https://www.buckeyextra.com/sports/20191213/ohio-state-football--chase-young-heisman-finalist-despite-playing-defense-being-suspended |archive-date=December 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nYoung won several awards and honors for his performance that season, including the [[Bronko Nagurski Trophy]],<ref name=\"Bronko\">{{cite web |last1=Straka |first1=Dean |title=Ohio State DE Chase Young wins Bronko Nagurski Trophy |url=https://247sports.com/Article/ohio-state-defensive-end-chase-young-wins-2019-bronko-nagurski-trophy-140221610/ |website=[[247Sports.com]] |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref> [[Chuck Bednarik Award]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Chase Young Wins 2019 Chuck Bednarik Award |url=https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/chase-young-wins-2019-bednarik-award/ |website=OhioStateBuckeyes.com |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103195746/https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/chase-young-wins-2019-bednarik-award/ |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Ted Hendricks Award]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clay |first1=Jarrod |title=Chase Young wins 2019 Ted Hendricks Award |url=https://abc6onyourside.com/sports/the-football-fever/chase-young-wins-2019-ted-hendricks-award |website=ABC 6 |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103195619/https://abc6onyourside.com/sports/the-football-fever/chase-young-wins-2019-ted-hendricks-award |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Chicago Tribune Silver Football]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greenstein |first1=Teddy |title=Chase Young is the 2019 Chicago Tribune Silver Football winner \u2014 and the 1st Ohio State defensive player to win the award in its 95-year history |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/college/ct-chase-young-ohio-state-silver-football-20191206-imh2o6cs45cpdbj5e7b7sla4zu-story.html |website=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230142145/https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/college/ct-chase-young-ohio-state-silver-football-20191206-imh2o6cs45cpdbj5e7b7sla4zu-story.html |archive-date=December 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Nagurski\u2013Woodson Defensive Player of the Year]],<ref name=\"Bronko\"/> and [[Smith\u2013Brown Defensive Lineman of the Year]].<ref name=\"Bronko\"/> In addition, he was twice named the [[Walter Camp Award|Walter Camp]] defensive player of the week for his performances against Wisconsin and Penn State,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hass-Hill |first1=Colin |title=Chase Young Named Walter Camp National Defensive Player Of The Week For Second Time This Season |url=https://www.elevenwarriors.com/ohio-state-football/2019/11/109337/chase-young-named-walter-camp-national-defensive-player-of-the-week-for-second-time-this-season |website=Elevan Warriors |accessdate=March 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127222424/https://www.elevenwarriors.com/ohio-state-football/2019/11/109337/chase-young-named-walter-camp-national-defensive-player-of-the-week-for-second-time-this-season |archive-date=November 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and was [[List of unanimous All-Americans in college football|unanimously named]] to the 2019 All-Big Ten and [[2019 College Football All-America Team|All-America Teams]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Big Ten Announces Football All-Conference Teams for Defense and Special Teams and Select Individual Honors |url=https://bigten.org/news/2019/12/3/big-ten-announces-football-all-conference-teams-for-defense-and-special-teams-and-select-individual-honors.aspx |website=BigTen.org |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204022652/https://bigten.org/news/2019/12/3/big-ten-announces-football-all-conference-teams-for-defense-and-special-teams-and-select-individual-honors.aspx |archive-date=December 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was also named a finalist for the [[Walter Camp Award]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rosvoglou |first1=Chris |title=5 Finalists Announced For Walter Camp Player Of The Year |url=https://thespun.com/big-ten/ohio-state-buckeyes/finalists-announced-for-walter-camp-player-of-the-year |website=The Spun |accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref> [[Maxwell Award]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Duffley |first1=John |title=Joe Burrow Wins Maxwell Award as CFB\u2019s Player of the Year |url=https://fanbuzz.com/college-football/maxwell-award-watch-list/ |website=FanBuzz.com |accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref> and [[Heisman Trophy]], becoming only the ninth defensive player since 1982 to be nominated for the latter, where he finished fourth in voting behind quarterbacks [[Joe Burrow]], [[Jalen Hurts]], and [[Justin Fields]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cross |first1=Ian |title=OSU defensive end Chase Young declares for 2020 NFL Draft |url=https://www.news5cleveland.com/sports/college-sports/osu/osu-defensive-end-chase-young-declares-for-2020-nfl-draft |website=News 5 Cleveland |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104141151/https://www.news5cleveland.com/sports/college-sports/osu/osu-defensive-end-chase-young-declares-for-2020-nfl-draft |archive-date=January 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author1=ESPN News Services |title=Bayou bliss: LSU QB Joe Burrow takes home Heisman |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/28298763/bayou-bliss-lsu-qb-joe-burrow-takes-home-heisman |website=ESPN |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230123538/https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/28298763/bayou-bliss-lsu-qb-joe-burrow-takes-home-heisman |archive-date=December 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He finished his career at Ohio State with 30.5 total sacks, which ranks second all-time there behind [[Mike Vrabel]]'s 36.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anders |first1=Andy |title=Football: Chase Young declares for NFL Draft |url=https://www.thelantern.com/2020/01/ohio-state-football-chase-young-declares-for-nfl-draft-2/ |website=The Latern |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406225649/https://www.thelantern.com/2020/01/ohio-state-football-chase-young-declares-for-nfl-draft-2/ |archive-date=April 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2|Season\n! colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"2\" |Games\n! colspan=4|Tackles\n! colspan=2|Sacks\n! colspan=2|Fumbles\n|-\n! Solo !! Ast !! Total !! TFL !! Total !! Yards\n!FF\n!FR\n|-\n![[2017 Ohio State Buckeyes football season|2017]]\n|9\n|11\n|7\n|18\n|5\n|3.5\n|20\n|1\n| rowspan=\"3\" |0\n|-\n![[2018 Ohio State Buckeyes football season|2018]]\n|13\n|25\n|9\n|34\n|14.5\n|10.5\n|60\n|1\n|-\n![[2019 Ohio State Buckeyes football season|2019]]\n|12\n|32\n|14\n|46\n|21\n|16.5\n|117\n|7\n|-\n! Totals<ref>{{cite web |title=Chase Young College Stats |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/chase-young-1.html |website=sports-reference.com |publisher=College Football Reference |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408093051/https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/chase-young-1.html |archive-date=April 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n!34\n!68||30||98||40.5||30.5||197\n!9\n!0\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nYoung decided to forgo his senior year at Ohio State by declaring for the [[2020 NFL Draft]],<ref>{{cite web |author1=ESPN |title=Ohio State DE Chase Young announces he's entering NFL draft |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/28416265/ohio-state-de-chase-young-announces-entering-nfl-draft |website=ESPN |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103191232/https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/28416265/ohio-state-de-chase-young-announces-entering-nfl-draft |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Shook |first1=Nick |title=Ohio State DE Chase Young declares for 2020 draft |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001094141/article/ohio-state-de-chase-young-declares-for-2020-draft |website=NFL.com |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103195556/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001094141/article/ohio-state-de-chase-young-declares-for-2020-draft |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> where he is considered by many to be its best overall prospect.<ref name=\"SportingNews\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Birkett |first1=Dave |title=Chase Young is NFL draft's No. 1 prospect; don't let late-season slump worry you |url=https://www.freep.com/story/sports/nfl/lions/2020/02/24/chase-young-ohio-state-football-nfl-draft/4856539002/ |website=Detroit Free Press |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225215049/https://www.freep.com/story/sports/nfl/lions/2020/02/24/chase-young-ohio-state-football-nfl-draft/4856539002/ |archive-date=February 25, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=McAtee |first1=Riley |title=Chase Young and the Perennial Draft Appeal of an Elite Pass Rusher |url=https://www.theringer.com/nfl/2020/4/13/21218550/2020-nfl-draft-chase-young-defensive-end-prospects-trend |website=[[The Ringer]] |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> He attended the [[NFL Combine]] but did not participate in any workouts or drills, stating that he did not want to waste time being a \"combine athlete\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=DelVecchio |first1=Steve |title=Chase Young has great explanation for skipping combine workouts |url=https://www.yardbarker.com/nfl/articles/chase_young_has_great_explanation_for_skipping_combine_workouts/s1_127_31450310 |website=[[Yardbarker]] |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303053338/https://www.yardbarker.com/nfl/articles/chase_young_has_great_explanation_for_skipping_combine_workouts/s1_127_31450310 |archive-date=March 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Young was one of 58 players invited to the draft, which is to be held virtually due to [[social distancing]] regulations arising from the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |author1=Around The NFL staff |title=58 prospects to virtually participate in NFL draft |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001108866/article/58-prospects-to-virtually-participate-in-nfl-draft |website=NFL.com |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200410064948/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001108866/article/58-prospects-to-virtually-participate-in-nfl-draft |archive-date=April 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nYoung's father, Greg, played college basketball at [[Bowie State University]] before working as a police deputy with the [[Arlington County Sheriff's Office]], while his mother, Carla, works for the [[Office of Investigations for the Department of Transportation]].<ref name=\"Dayton\"/><ref name=\"Law\">{{cite web |last1=Means |first1=Stephen |title=Ohio State\u2019s star DE Chase Young following his family\u2019s formula to success: From athletics to law enforcement |url=https://www.cleveland.com/osu/2019/09/ohio-states-star-de-chase-young-following-his-familys-formula-to-success-from-athletics-to-law-enforcement.html |website=Cleveland.com |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191003205731/https://www.cleveland.com/osu/2019/09/ohio-states-star-de-chase-young-following-his-familys-formula-to-success-from-athletics-to-law-enforcement.html |archive-date=October 3, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"2PointStance\">{{cite web |last1=Goodbread |first1=Chase |title=Two-Point Stance |url=http://www.nfl.com/labs/cfb247/chase-young/chase-young |website=NFL.com |accessdate=April 16, 2020 |date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Young has a sister, Weslie, who played college basketball at [[North Carolina Wesleyan]].<ref name=\"Tattoo\">{{cite web |last1=Culpepper |first1=Chuck |title=A veteran and grandfather\u2019s kinetic tribute \u2014 on the arm of college football\u2019s best player |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/11/22/chase-young-grandfather-tattoo-nfl-ohio-state-college-football/ |website=[[Washington Post]] |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229110140/https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/11/22/chase-young-grandfather-tattoo-nfl-ohio-state-college-football/ |archive-date=December 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> At Ohio State, Young pursued a [[major (academics)|major]] in [[criminology]] after being inspired by his father and several of his uncles and cousins, who all work in [[law enforcement]].<ref name=\"Law\"/><ref name=\"2PointStance\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Chase Young, DeMatha Catholic, Weak-Side Defensive End |url=https://247sports.com/Player/Chase-Young-83154/high-school-144085/ |website=[[247Sports.com]] |accessdate=May 10, 2019}}</ref> He is sometimes called the \"Predator\" for his on-field dominance, as well as his [[dreadlock]]s resembling [[Predator (fictional species)|Predators]] from the ''[[Predator (franchise)|Predator]]'' franchise.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thamel |first1=Pete |title=Why freaky OSU DE Chase Young is the best player in college football: \u2018There\u2019s only 10 guys like him in the world\u2019 |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/chase-young-best-player-in-college-football-154802867.html |website=sports.yahoo.com |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101104924/https://sports.yahoo.com/chase-young-best-player-in-college-football-154802867.html |archive-date=January 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hooley |first1=Bruce |title=Jackson Carman Eluded Ohio State; will Block Chase Young |url=https://www.si.com/college/ohiostate/football/jackson-carman-eluded-ohio-state-now-will-block-chase-young |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225151946/https://www.si.com/college/ohiostate/football/jackson-carman-eluded-ohio-state-now-will-block-chase-young |archive-date=December 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hooley |first1=Bruce |title=Ohio State's Chase Young May Be Better Than Bosa Brothers |url=https://www.si.com/college/ohiostate/football/ohio-states-chase-young-may-be-better-than-bosa-brothers |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Young has a tattoo of Carl H. Robinson, his late grandfather and [[US Air Force]] veteran, on his right arm.<ref name=\"Tattoo\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{twitter|youngchase907}}\n* [https://www.nfl.com/prospects/chase-young?id=3219594f-5514-6550-d662-263c81d981b1 NFL.com prospect profile]\n* [http://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/roster/chase-young/ Ohio State Buckeyes bio]\n\n{{Navboxes|title=Chase Young|list=\n{{Bronko Nagurski Trophy}}\n{{Chuck Bednarik Award}}\n{{Ted Hendricks Award}}\n{{Chicago Tribune Silver Football navbox}}\n{{2019 NCAA Division I FBS College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Young, Chase}}\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:American football defensive ends]]\n[[Category:DeMatha Catholic High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ohio State Buckeyes football players]]\n[[Category:People from Upper Marlboro, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from the Washington metropolitan area]]\n", "name_user": "Dissident93", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chase_Young"}
{"title_page": "Kokey at Ako", "text_new": "{{For|town in Benin|Kokey, Benin}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Kokey at Ako\n| image                = MALIGNO2008.jpg\n| caption              =\n| genre                = [[Comedy]], [[Drama]], [[Fantasy]]\n| creator              = Rondel P. Lindayag\n| developer            = Laurenti M. Dyogi\n| writer               = \n| director             = [[Wenn V. Deramas]]\n| executive_producer   = \n| production_manager   = \n| creative_manager     = \n| starring             = [[Vhong Navarro]]<br />[[Toni Gonzaga]]\n| theme_music_composer = \n| opentheme            = \"Kokey @ Ako\" by Toni Gonzaga, Vhong Navarro, [[Melai Cantiveros]] and [[Jason Francisco]]\n| endtheme             = \n| composer             = [[Vincent de Jesus]]\n| country              = [[Philippines]]\n| language             = [[Filipino language|Filipino]], [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]], English\n| num_episodes         = 55\n| location             = Philippines\n| cinematography       = \n| editor               = Sidney Zaid Pascua\n| network              = [[ABS-CBN (TV network)|ABS-CBN]]\n| runtime              = 30 minutes\n| company              = [[Star Cinema|Star Creatives]]\n| picture_format       = [[480i]] ([[SDTV]])\n| first_aired          = {{start date|2010|9|20}}\n| last_aired           = {{end date|2010|12|3}}\n| preceded_by          = ''[[Momay]]''\n| related              = ''[[Kokey]]''\n| website              = http://kokeyatako.abs-cbn.com\n}}\n'''Kokey at Ako''' (stylized as '''Kokey @ Ako''', {{translation|Kokey and Me}}) is a 2010 [[Philippines|Philippine]] [[comedy]]-[[fantasy]] drama series that serves as a sequel to the 2007 TV series [[Kokey]]. Directed by [[Wenn V. Deramas]], the series stars [[Toni Gonzaga]] and [[Vhong Navarro]] with [[Melai Cantiveros]], with an [[ensemble cast]] consisting of [[Gloria Romero (actress)|Ms. Gloria Romero]], [[Jason Francisco]], [[Mickey Ferriols]], [[Maricel Laxa]], [[Christian Vasquez]], [[Wendy Valdez]], Mike Lloren, [[Joy Viado]], Tess Antonio, [[Francis Magundayao]], Yulio Pisk, [[Empoy Marquez]], Debralis Velasote, [[DJ Durano]], [[Candy Pangilinan]], [[Bugoy Cari\u00f1o]], Philip Nolasco, and Macky Billiones in their supporting roles. The series premiered on [[ABS-CBN (TV network)|ABS-CBN]]'s ''Primetime Bida'' nighttime block, replacing ''[[Momay]]'' from September 20 to December 3, 2010.<ref>[http://www.push.com.ph/news-feature/329/-Kokey-at-Ako-lands-on-ABS-CBN-primetime-bida.aspx \u2018Kokey at Ako\u2019 lands on ABS-CBN primetime bida]</ref>\n\n==Plot summary==\nThe series follows the [[Extraterrestrial life|alien]] Kokey and the human [[reporter]] Jackie as they work to reunite with their families while the aliens from Planet Kukurikabu plot to exterminate mankind.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n\n<!--Official cast billing from ABS-CBN.-->\n===Cast===\n====Main cast====\n*[[Vhong Navarro]] as Bruce Kho / Belat\n*[[Toni Gonzaga]] as Princess/Jackie Reyes\n*[[Melai Cantiveros]] as Josa Reyes\n\n====Supporting cast====\n*[[Gloria Romero (actress)|Gloria Romero]] as Barbara Reyes\n*[[Jason Francisco]] as Adonis\n*[[Mickey Ferriols]] as Annie Reyes\n*[[Maricel Laxa|Maricel Laxa-Pangilinan]] as Dianne Reyes\n*[[Christian Vasquez]] as Roland Reyes\n*[[Wendy Valdez]] as Lois Magsanoc\n*Mike Lloren as King Cone\n*[[Joy Viado]]\u2020 as Bebot\n*Tess Antonio as Babet\n*[[Francis Magundayao]]/Yulio Pisk as Belat\n*[[Empoy Marquez]] as Bubot\n*Debralis Velasote as Vangie\n*[[DJ Durano]] as Dr. DJ Caparas\n*[[Candy Pangilinan]] as Cynthia Caparas\n*[[Bugoy Cari\u00f1o]] as Caloy\n*Philip Nolasco as JD Caparas\n*Macky Billiones as Ni\u00f1o\n\n====Extended cast====\n*Rubi-Rubi Esmaquel as Fifi\n*Jojit Lorenzo as Dick\n*Atak Arana as Atak\n*Eric Nicolas as Tom\n*[[Simon Ibarra]] as Jerry\n*Minco Fabregas as Tinnio Tan\n*Mark Valdez as Antony Precie\n*[[Joseph Andre Garcia]] as Baldo\n*Marissa Orillo\n\n====Special participation====\n*[[Dennis Padilla]] as Eduardo \"Chong Edong\" Reyes\n*[[Nova Villa]] as Sor Aida Sanchez\n*Abby Bautista as young Princess Reyes / Jackie Reyes\n*[[Amy Nobleza]] as young Josa Reyes\n*Frenchie Dy/[[Kiray Celis]] (young) as Bam-Bam\n*Frances Ignacio as Toribia\n*[[Johan Santos]] as Mike\n*Tanya Gomez as Linda Magsanoc\n*[[Jairus Aquino]] as Rolly / Young Roland\n*Cheska Billiones as Nena / Young Dianne\n*Jewel Crisanto as Ada (Caloy's playmate in the adoption center)\n*Marissa Orillo as herself\n*Emerson Lee as boarding mate\n\n===Characters===\n====Earthlings====\n*[[Toni Gonzaga]]/Abby Bautista (''young'') as Princess Reyes / Jackie Reyes<ref name=\"Vhong Navarro and Toni Gonzaga\">{{Cite web| url = http://www.abs-cbn.com/Feature/Article/6896/Vhong-Navarro-and-Toni-Gonzaga-pair-up-for-Kokey-at-Ako.aspx | title = Vhong Navarro and Toni Gonzaga pair up for Kokey at Ako | work = Showbuzz | publisher = ABS-CBN News | author = Quintos, Napoleon | date = 2010-03-12 | accessdate = 2010-09-02}}</ref> - Jackie is a survivor from a [[massacre]] plot against her family, an [[alien abduction]], growing up without parents to provide her needs, and moving on with life with no memory of her real identity. Despite her traumatic past, Jackie is a positive thinker. She is a resourceful and determined news reporter with a special interest in [[paranormal]] and [[Extraterrestrial life|extraterrestrial]] activities. She is obsessed with retracing the events of the past\u2014looking for any leads of alien movements, hoping to find possible indications of her parents\u2019 whereabouts. And that vital lead may be Kokey. The role was originally given to [[Angel Locsin]].<ref name=\"Enrique\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.abs-cbn.com/Celebrity/Article/5798/Enrique-Gil-stars-in-the-upcoming-teleserye-Kokey-Ako-.aspx|title=Enrique Gil stars in the upcoming teleserye \u2018Kokey @ Ako\u2019|work=Celeb Highlight|author=Quintos, Napoleon|publisher=Showbuzz|date=3 December 2009|accessdate=20 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091207013349/http://www.abs-cbn.com/Celebrity/Article/5798/Enrique-Gil-stars-in-the-upcoming-teleserye-Kokey-Ako-.aspx|archive-date=7 December 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> Locsin was replaced by Gonzaga due to Locsin's commitment to [[Imortal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/news/25011/Angel-Locsin-pulled-out-from-Kokey@Ako|title=Angel Locsin pulled out from Kokey@Ako }}</ref>\n*[[Vhong Navarro]]/ Kyle Balili (''young'')\n:*as Bruce Kho Reyes<ref name=\"Vhong Navarro and Toni Gonzaga\"/> - Bruce used to be the boy who fell in love with the little rich girl with no memory. He is Jackie\u2019s best friend, confidante and companion in the search for her missing parents. The hard work and sacrifices he made paid off when his one great love accepted his proposal to be his wife. One day before the wedding, Bruce accepts a news coverage that leads to an unfortunate accident of stellar proportions. Bruce seems to get mad at Bam-Bam (Toribia's Daughter) and helping Jackie and Josa as Bam-Bam teases them.\n:*as Belat - ''See: [[Kokey @ Ako#Kukurikabukans|Belat]]''\n*[[Melai Cantiveros]]/ Amy Nobleza (''young'') as Josa Reyes - Josa sees and does everything in a different way---odd but funny. She is Bruce's cousin, and Jackie's best friend and pseudo-sister. Her carefree attitude is refreshing, but would often lead to a lot of hilarious misadventures.\n*[[Jason Francisco]] as Adonis - Adonis had been training as a [[cameraman]] for Channel Z for the last six years but can't get a promotion. When Bruce starts working for the station, Adonis becomes one of his good friends. Adonis eventually becomes Josa's [[love interest]].\n*[[Gloria Romero (actress)|Ms. Gloria Romero]] as Barbara Reyes - Madam Barbra is a sophisticated woman who owns a TV network, Z Broadcasting Company, as well as several companies. Her authority cannot be questioned, but behind her straightforward, stern and unyielding command is a grandmother longing to be reunited with her long-lost son and granddaughter.\n*[[Mickey Ferriols]] as Annie Reyes - Annie is Barbara's adopted daughter. She is insecure so she had done bad plans. She is the one who planned to kill Jackie (Princess)'s family. When the years passed, she wants to get the company (Z Broadcasting Company), and she knew that Jackie is Princess. So, she used Lois, to pretend to be Princess Reyes, the long-lost granddaughter of Barbara, but all of her plans didn't work. In the last episode, She vanished after she used her powers.\n*[[Wendy Valdez]] as Lois Magsanoc - Jackie's rival to the heart of Bruce and she pretended to be Princess Reyes (which Annie planned) because of her ambition to be an actress. When the truth was known that she is not the real Princess because Barbara saw her mother, a crazy one. And instead of being mad, she helped Barbara's family, even Jackie.\n\n====Yekokans (unnamed actors thanks to abs cbn)====\n*Kokey - Kokey returns to Planet Earth to find his missing sister before she unwittingly wreaks havoc on mankind. In his search for his furry sibling, Kokey gets to meet new friends and goes into another roller-coaster adventure ride of his life.\n*Kekay - Kekay is Kokey's jealous furry little sister. She was born thinking she was disliked and unloved by her parents, and grew up envious over her brother's popularity not only in Planet Yekok but on Earth as well. Her sense of curiosity and misadventure sends her to an accidental journey to Earth.\n*Umamay Kakay - Kokey and Kekay's mother.\n*Tay Kokoy - Kokey and Kekay's father.\n\n====Kukurikabukans====\n*Mike Lloren as King Cone - King Cone is the ruthless ruler of planet Kukurikabu. Disobedience of his orders will mean death to any human or exile to outer space for Kukurikabukans.\n*[[Joy Viado]] as Bebot - One of the three elders of the more than 350 children spawned by King Cone. They are ruthless and heartless as their father; very much enthusiastic in brewing plans to invade other planets, particularly Earth, to call their second home.\n*Tess Antonio as Babet - One of the three elders of the more than 350 children spawned by King Cone. They are ruthless and heartless as their father; very much enthusiastic in brewing plans to invade other planets, particularly Earth, to call their second home.\n*[[Francis Magundayao]] as Belat - Prince Belat is one of the thousands of King Cone's kids. He is affectionate and caring towards the human prisoners of his father, an unthinkable and forbidden behavior for children of [[royal family|royalty]]. The young prince is most especially attached to Dianne, whom he treated as his mother. Belat's attachment to Dianne drove him to invent a spaceship to send the human couple back to their home planet. As Belat attempts to fly his alien craft to Earth, an accident occurs leaving him trapped in Bruce's body.\n*[[Empoy Marquez]] as Bubot - One of the three elders of the more than 350 children spawned by King Cone. They are ruthless and heartless as their father; very much enthusiastic in brewing plans to invade other planets, particularly Earth, to call their second home.\n\n==Production==\n{{Empty section|date=April 2015}}\n\n==Reception==\n===Launch===\n''Kokey at Ako'' was postponed three times before it was given an official premiere date. It was originally announced as one of the [[ABS-CBN]]'s offering for the 60th Celebration of Filipino Soap Opera (''Ika-60 taon ng Pinoy Soap Opera''), during the ABS-CBN Trade Launch for the first quarter of 2010, entitled ''Bagong Simula'' (New Beginning).<ref name=\"abs-cbn.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.abs-cbn.com/Headlines/Article/1800/The-biggest-stars-descend-on-Bagong-Simula-the-ABS-CBN-Trade-Show.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-09-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305232712/http://www2.abs-cbn.com/headlines/article/1800/the-biggest-stars-descend-on-bagong-simula-the-abs-cbn-trade-show.aspx |archive-date=2014-03-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHowever, it was postponed and was launched again as one of the ABS-CBN's offerings for the second quarter of 2010, during the ABS-CBN Trade Launch and was announced during the ''Kapamilya Trade Launch'' held in Boracay.<ref name=\"abs-cbn.com\"/>\n\nThe show was later announced as half-term show line-up by ABS-CBN as part of the 60th Anniversary of Philippines Television and was presented as the station's ID for the [[rainy season]] in the Philippines.<ref>[http://www.pep.ph/news/26226/Kantar-Media/TNS-National-Household-Ratings-(July-16-18):-Showtime-and--Julaton-fight-are-weekend-daytime-winners]</ref> The trailer premiered on June 26, 2010 on its official website.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.islanoah.com/ |title=Noah's website |access-date=2010-09-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100629222036/http://www.islanoah.com/ |archive-date=2010-06-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of programs broadcast by ABS-CBN]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{ABS-CBN Adaptations (Local Films)}}\n{{ABS-CBN telenovelas}}\n\n[[Category:2010 Philippine television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010 Philippine television series endings]]\n[[Category:ABS-CBN drama series]]\n[[Category:Fantaserye and telefantasya]]\n[[Category:Filipino-language television programs]]\n[[Category:2010s children's television series]]\n[[Category:Philippine comedy television series]]\n[[Category:Philippine drama television series]]\n[[Category:Television series by Star Creatives]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in the Philippines]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|town in Benin|Kokey, Benin}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Kokey at Ako\n| image                = MALIGNO2008.jpg\n| caption              =\n| genre                = [[Comedy]], [[Drama]], [[Fantasy]]\n| creator              = Rondel P. Lindayag\n| developer            = Laurenti M. Dyogi\n| writer               = \n| director             = [[Wenn V. Deramas]]\n| executive_producer   = \n| production_manager   = 